h3. Issue Summary
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a page in Confluence in origin space
 # Copy page to target space using API
 # Create a new property in the original page
 # Copy page again using API

 
{code:java}
// Initial copy page 
POST /wiki/rest/api/content/{{sourcePageId}}/copy
{
  copyCustomContents: false,
  copyAttachments: true,
  copyLabels: true,
  copyProperties: true,
  destination: { type: 'parent_page', value: '{{target-spaces-homepage-id}}' },
  body: {
    storage: { value: '<p>testing</p>', representation: 'storage' }
  }
}

// Success
{
  id: '12345789',
  type: 'page',
  ..................
}

// Create a new simple content property on source page
POST /wiki/rest/api/content/{{sourcePageId}}/property 
body:
{
  "key": "hello",
  "value": "world"
}

// Copy page again
POST /wiki/rest/api/content/{{sourcePageId}}/copy
{
  copyCustomContents: false,
  copyAttachments: true,
  copyLabels: true,
  copyProperties: true,
  destination: { type: 'existing_page', value: '12345789' },
  body: {
    storage: {
      value: '<p>test again</p>',
      representation: 'storage'
    }
  }
}

// Error received
{ message: 'java.lang.NullPointerException: null', status: 500 }{code}
 
h3. Expected Results

Page is updated correctly and the newly created property exists in destination page
h3. Actual Results
{noformat}
{"statusCode": 500, "message": "java.lang.NullPointerException: null" }
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

{panel}
It would be great if we can have a feature where if space was specified with the anonymous access and later on modified. It should have the possibility to list the history of  modifications/ access list specified in the audit logs for record purposes.
{panel}

h3. Issue Summary
It is awesome how we can customize the default templates that Confluence has - this way, we can always have things according to our own needs!
When we decide to edit the *Default Space Content* template (the one that will create the overview pages for each new space), inserting the *Notes Panel* (the purple one) makes the content get rid when the space is created, creating a space overview with empty content.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Navigate to *Settings > Global Templates and Blueprints*;
# Go down until you find the *Default Space Content* template;
# Edit it;
# Add some very random content, it can be some Lorem Ipsum text;
# Anywhere in the template, place a *Notes Panel* (once again, the purple one);
# Save the template;
# Create a new blank space.

h3. Expected Results
The overview page of the new space has all the content you inserted in the template.

h3. Actual Results
The overview page is empty.


h3. Workaround
Please, try using a different panel macro in the template until we get this fixed.

In Editor Settings, there is a configuration item that will be able to configure default page width to full.

In this context, "full-width" should translate to "全幅" not "全角".

 

Original text.
{quote}Enable full-width as the default for new pages.
{quote}
Japanese translation (incorrect)
{quote}{{全角を新規ページのデフォルトとして有効にします。}}{quote}
Japanese translation (correct)
{quote}{{全幅を新規ページのデフォルトとして有効にします。}}{quote}

h3. Issue Summary
Playing with tables on Confluence is always a great option to keep things in order. It is nice how we can easily copy and paste table content from a table into another one, which let the experience really great!
Though, we have to take care when copying determined types of content between tables, like the header row from a table to another one, as this makes Confluence reads that the table where we pasted it as if it has two headers.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page and insert a table;
# On the table header, type *1*, *2*, and *3* on each of the header cells;
# Create another table under the current one;
# At the header, insert *A*, *B*, and *C*;
# Add more 20 table rows;
# On the first table, copy its header (select it all until the row gets blue and copy it);
# Paste it on the 10th row of the second table;
# Publish the page;
# Edit it and scroll the second table.

h3. Expected Results
The content from the copied row gets pasted as a regular row, not a header
*OR*
The table supports multiple headers.

h3. Actual Results
The table rows get broken - as much content you have in the table, worse the experience gets.

h3. Workaround
After editing the page, in the issued table, remove and then re-add the *header row*.

(!) This workaround must be applied every time we edit the page, as it is a momentaneously solution for each time you are editing the page.

----

You can also delete the pasted header row and manually add its content there, so the table will contain a single header and will work fine. 
In order to identify which is the duplicated header, go to the affected page in the *view mode* and click over the *ellipses > Page Source* - navigate to the broken table and identify which table row has the text highlighted with a gray background-color - in case the entire row is grey, then it is probably also the second header.

h3. Issue Summary
The *Team Calendars* add-on is a great feature that helps us keep tracking things on Confluence. The possibility to create a different calendar with a timezone that is apart from our own, as well from our site, is amazing for companies that work with global teams!
Working with weekly events, though, can sometimes present us with an issue identified when the calendar is set with *Asia/Tokyo (+0900)* timezone and the period of the day on your event is on PM time.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a new calendar anywhere in your site - make sure to set the timezone to *Asia/Tokyo (+0900)*;
# On this new calendar, create a new event on Friday (everybody loves Friday, that's why);
# Set the following fields like this:
** *When*: the day you chose but make sure the start and end times are set to PM;
** *All day event*: uncheck this, so you can edit above info;
** *Repeat*: Weekly - every Friday;
# Save the event.

h3. Expected Results
The events are created on every Friday.

h3. Actual Results
The first event gets created on Friday, but the following ones on every Thursday.

*Notes*:
* This issue could be affecting more timezones, but we would need to check it further.

h3. Workaround
Edit the first event and:
# Uncheck the *_Edit this instance only_* option;
# Change the start time to AM;
# Save the event;
# Note it changed to all Fridays, edit the event again and change the start time back to PM:
** Again, don't forget to uncheck *_Edit this instance only_*.

h3. Issue Summary
The third-party add-on [MultiExcerpt|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/apps/169/multiexcerpt?hosting=cloud&tab=overview], developed and supported by [Artemis Software|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/vendors/84/artemis-software] provides us with some cool additional macros to use on Confluence.
It seems that when we are setting up some pages to use some of its macros, exporting the space and importing on a new site makes the macros within the pages to lose the relation from the pages they are excerpting content.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# You will need two Confluence Cloud sites;
# Make sure to install the [MultiExcerpt|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/apps/169/multiexcerpt?hosting=cloud&tab=overview] add-on on both sites;
# On site A, create three pages:
** on page #1, add the MultiExcerpt macro with content to be excerpted;
** on page #2, add the MultiExcerpt macro that will call the content from page #1, and also add a MultiExcerpt macro with content to be excerpted on other page;
** on page #3, use the MultiExcerpt macros to call both contents from Page #1 and #2;
# Export the space to XML;
# After downloading the exported file, go to site B;
# Navigate to *Settings > Import Space* and import the exported space from site A;
# Access page #2.

h3. Expected Results
The content within the macros are being shown as expected.

h3. Actual Results
The macros eventually won't show the content with an error message saying that the pages where the content is being referenced couldn't be shown.

*Notes*:
* Navigating through the pages in the space and then going back to page #2 will make the content appear again.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
When setting how much results we would like to see per page in the *Page Properties Report* macro if it is more than 50, it won't show the number of results we set.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create 100 pages with the *Page Properties* macro added, as well with the label {{bug-report}};
# Create a new page;
# Insert the *Page Properties Report* macro and set it to get all pages from the current space with the label {{bug-report}};
# In the macro settings, expand the options;
# On the "_Number of items to display_", set it to get 51 pages (or even all the 100);
# Save the macro and publish the page.

h3. Expected Results
The 51 (or the amount you set) are being shown on the first page of the macro.

h3. Actual Results
Only the first 50 results are being shown.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
When we are using images within a *Page Properties* macro, it usually gets shown in the *Page Properties Report* macro in another page, but it seems to be broken at this moment.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page;
# Insert the *Page Properties* macro;
# Make sure to add an image in the table within the properties (it can be a random screenshot);
# Publish the page;
# Insert the label {{image}};
# Create a new page;
# Insert the *Page Properties Report* macro;
# Set it to call all pages within the space with the {{image}} label;
# Publish the page.

h3. Expected Results
The report shows the image from the first page you created.

h3. Actual Results
It shows the image broken with the *Retry* option, to try to reload the image.

*Notes*:
* It returns a 403 error in the browser console with the below response:
{code}{"error":{"code":"JwtAuthoriser:AuthorisationError","title":"The token does not allow requested operation. \"urn:filestore:collection:contentId-646119430\" needs \"read\" permission","href":"https://api.media.atlassian.com#UnauthorizedError"}}{code}

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
The *Page Properties Report* macro is no longer showing the pagination when the total results are over 50 pages.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create 100 pages with the new editor, containing a *Page Properties* macro;
# Add a label on those pages called {{label-test}};
# Create a new page;
# Insert the *Page Properties Report* macro, calling all the pages within the same space that have the {{label-test}} label;
# Publish the page.

h3. Expected Results
As the pagination limit is not working, the macro should show us 2 pages with 50 results each.

h3. Actual Results
There is no pagination, only 50 results in the macro.

*Notes*:
* The default behavior of the macro is arranging the results by alphabetical order in the first column:
** *Hit the first header column once*: it will show the last 50 results from the last page, from A to Z;
** *Hit the first header column twice*:  it will show the last 50 results from the last page, from Z to A;
** *Hit it a third time*: it back to show the original results.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available
